FOUR! BOOM! This one is off the middle of the bat. Full and just outside off, Harris punches it on the up and it races down to the long off fence.
Fuller and around off, pushed hard but straight to mid on.

EDGED AND FOUR! Natarajan bowls this one fuller and just around middle, it moves away again. Harris looks to defend but the ball takes the outside edge and falls short of Rohit at second slip who dives to his right but fails to get there. The ball sneaks through and goes to the fence.
Another leave from Harris as Natarajan bowls this one wide outside off.
Natarajan starts with a length ball outside off, it shapes away a touch as Harris watches it go into the gloves of Pant behind the wickets.
T Natarajan to bowl from the other end. 3-0-6-0 are his figures so far.
Length and around off, Warner defends off his back foot and a loud no follows. Top first over from Siraj. He has gone past the outside edge twice in this over.
That's a jaffa from Siraj. Very good start from him. Pitches this one on middle and leg and makes it to angle away. Warner looks to play at it but is beaten.
Length ball outside off, Warner makes a leave.
FOUR! Warner is away on Day 4! A fullish ball just outside off, Warner strokes it through mid off and finds the fence. That should tell you the approach he has in his mind.
Back of a length and just around off again, this time Warner gets on top of the bounce and pushes it towards point.
Beaten first ball! Terrific start from Siraj. Shortish and just outside off, moving away. Warner has a tentative push at it. He is beaten all ends up there.

We are all set to begin the action on Day 4. The Indian players walk out to the middle as they take their respective fielding positions. David Warner and Marcus Harris too stride out to the middle. Mohammed Siraj to begin for the visitors. 2-1-12-0 are his figures so far.

Steven Smith is down for the chat. Tells that they started the day well but the partnership between Thakur and Sundar was the one which they failed to break. Adds that they would look to bat normally and score quickly as they have quality batting. Mentions that he has worked hard on his fielding and just tries to leave an impact wherever he can. He also says that it was a long day in the field and they just do one thing is to stay focused while on the field. Ends by saying that there is a storm predicted in the afternoon.

Pitch Report - Glenn McGrath says that the cracks are getting bigger and it is a bit unusual. The weather too will play its part. He further says that how these cracks will impact we will have to see.

Now, the most important question. How's the weather? Currently it is not raining but there are a lot of dark clouds hovering around at the moment. There is also a storm off the coast and there is quite a chance that it might make its way across the ground. For now, an on time start looks likely in all possibility and for later in the day fingers crossed. We hope that the weather remains clear and the storm stays off coast.

The visitors, on the other hand, won't mind a draw. Why? Well, a draw would mean that they retain the trophy they're playing for. However, a couple of early wickets would put them in the driver's seat. So, don't count them out. Surely not after their terrific performances after the slump from the first Test.

Hello everyone! Are you guys ready to witness yet another fascinating day's play in this Test? Well, it has been one excellent game so far. Like throughout the series, India managed to crawl back in the game from tough situations. Australia, now has a tough ask. If they are to force a result, they will have to score briskly and then set a total for the Indians. Trying to score briskly means they might lose a few wickets and that might put them under more pressure. With rain threat around, things become even tougher for them.
... Day 4, Session 1 ...

Now then! That marks the end of an amazing day's play! No one in the driver's seat as yet. Australia had a big chance. They couldn't as India punched above their weight with 1-Test old Shardul and debutant Sundar getting to their half tons. Now, with threats of rain looming on the 4th and 5th day, the Aussies will be under some sort of pressure. They will have to score a few quick runs, set a total, one that they will feel safe at. They will remember the last game where India managed to battle the entire day to force a draw. For now, it is done and dusted from Day 3. Join us for the 4th day of this game. The action will begin at 0930 local (2330 GMT, THE PREVIOUS DAY). We will look for your company again. Until then, it is goodbye from our side. Take care!

The Aussie openers had testing 6 overs to survive to close Day 3. Warner and Harris did that with Warner playing a few delightful strokes. Australia eventually ended the day with the lead of 54 runs. They have all the 10 wickets intact.

The Aussies, one would feel had a very tough day with the ball. They got the big wickets of Pujara and Rahane in the first session. After some resistance from Agarwal and Pant, they managed to remove those two as well. Hazlewood got the wickets of Pujara, Agarwal and Pant while Starc removed Rahane. However, after that things got tough for them as Sundar and Thakur made them work really hard. The duo punished the Aussie bowlers in all parts of the ground. It was Cummins who broke the stand but not before he and his mates were belted all over the park. The frustration could be seen on their faces as the duo went about their business. Edges were found but they never went in the hands. And, the Aussies lost the chance of taking a big first innings' lead. Hazlewood with a fifer ended up as their pick of the bowlers.

They returned for the final session and returned how. They kept going and hammered every bowler that came their way. Thakur first brought up his half ton off a maximum and Sundar followed it soon as he pushed one to mid off for a quick single to reach his milestone on debut. The stand was eventually broken by Cummins when Thakur was bowled for 67 and the stand worth 123 was broken. Sundar continued and battled hard and took India closer to the Aussie score. They eventually were bowled out for 335, giving away the lead of 33.

The day started with India starting cautiously but they saw Pujara and Rahane departing in the first session. However, the visitors managed to score 99 runs in that session and made sure the scoreboard was ticking with Agarwal and Pant in the middle at the end of it. The second session saw India lose both Agarwal and Pant in quick succession. Then came the show of grit, determination and talent from Sundar and Thakur. The duo saw off the entire second session, adding 67 in the meantime to force the Aussies on the back foot.

What a day, what an amazing day for the Indians! Take a bow, Washington Sundar! Take a bow, Shardul Thakur. Once again, the Indians have managed to force their way back in the game from difficult situations like they have done all series, especially after their torrid performance in the first Test.
In the channel outside off, shapes away again. Harris lets it be. With that, it is STUMPS ON DAY 3.
Back of a length and on middle, tucked on the leg side for a single.

Short and wide outside off, Warner reaches out towards backward point.
Floated around middle and leg, played back to the bowler again.
Looped up and on middle, pushed back to the bowler.

EDGY! Fuller and outside off, Warner is lured for the drive away from his body. He does that and the ball takes the thick outside edge. Flies uppishly through point. Three more for Warner.
Fuller but down the leg side. Warner looks to clip it on the leg side but misses.

Siraj starts off with a good length delivery outside off, Harris shoulders arms to this one.
We are back again! The Indians are out in the middle already. David Warner and Marcus Harris are the Aussie openers. Mohammed Siraj will take the ball first up for the Indians. Here we go...

Phew! Well, that's all from this long tour. The Indian team will return home now and host England for a long tour. 4 Tests, 5 T20Is and 3 ODIs. The Test series is set to begin on the 5th of February 2021. Australia, on the other hand, will travel to New Zealand for a 5-match T20I series which starts from 22nd February 2021. Join us for all those games. For now, we bid you goodbye! Cheers and take care!

That's quite a summary of the series! Let' talk about the entire tour too. Australia won the ODI series 2-1. India returned the favour by pocketing the T20I leg 2-1 and now the Test series has been pocketed by the Indians.

And then came this game! Key players like Ashwin, Bumrah, Jadeja and Vihari were out of this game. There were bio-bubble saga. The crowd issues in Sydney as well but Rahane's men took them all on the chin. The bowling attack looked inexperienced but boy what a performance from them throughout this game. They punched above their weight and kept themselves in the game. And then the hero with the bat, Rishabh Pant turned things around like a rockstar for the Indians.

That didn't happen though. Ajinkya Rahane led the unit in absence of Kohli and what followed was some unimaginable performances from the Indian team. Rahane led the team to a victory in the 2nd Test at the MCG! Then came SCG! And then came the fighting spirit of the Indian team. Injured players battled the entire day for them and made sure the 2nd Test was drawn. A number of heroes emerged for the visitors in that game. Heroes who didn't play the final Test because of the injuries.

Let's rewind the Test series! Virat Kohli-led Indian side got crushed at Adelaide in the first Test. Yes, crushed! 36 all out. And once that happened, everyone predicted that it is going to be a whitewash, with Virat Kohli gone home to be with his pregnant wife. India also missed the services of Shami for the remainder of the series.

Time for the victorious Indian skipper to have a word. Rahane says that the win means a lot to them. Is proud that the boys were brilliant after the Adelaide debacle. Tells they knew Australia at home is a very dangerous team. He mentions that the way Pujara batted and handled the pressure was superb. In the end, Rishabh and Sundar did brilliant work. Mentions that they went with 5 bowlers and Sundar gave them the balance. Tell that Siraj and Saini did good work to handle the pressure. He also says that they just wanted to play good cricket and express themselves. The Melbourne win was the key moment for them. Thanks the fans who came to support them. The Indian skipper ends by gifiting a signed jersey by all the Indians players to Nathan Lyon for playing 100 Tests. A terrific gesture from the Indian skipper and the entire team.

Tim Paine, the Aussie skipper to talk now. He says that they were here to win the game and the series but they have been outplayed by the better side. Says India fully deserve the series win. Tells that they need to look back at a few things. Says that they wanted to set the total over 300 and push for the series win. Feels India turned up for the day, wore balls on the helmet, on the fingers and put their body on the line. Tells that their bowlers tried everything they had with them but they were outplayed by the Indians.

PAT CUMMINS WINS THE PLAYER OF THE SERIES AWARD! Tells that it was a good hard day of Test cricket. Praises Pant and the Indian batters and tells that they deserved to win. Says that he wanted the cracks to show a few more tricks than it did. Feels that they had the chance of winning the game in Sydney and here on the 5th day but they couldn't do so. Says that they didn't take enough wickets to win the match.

RISHABH PANT IS NAMED PLAYER OF THE MATCH FOR HIS SUPERB KNOCK! He starts by saying that this is one of the biggest days of his life. He credits the entire support staff. Tells that it has been a dream series for them. Adds that he has been practicing hard and it paid off here. Says that the management has always backed him and they keep telling him that he is a match-winner. Tells he always wanted to win the game for the team. On him playing patiently, Pant mentions that it was the 5th day's wicket and he needed to make sure his shot selection were correct.

Australia extended their lead with the openers giving a strong start. India, as they have been throughout the series, made another comeback with quick strikes. Smith's half-century and contributions from the lower order saw Australia give India 328. Siraj and Shardul put on an inspired bowling performance with the former picking up his maiden Test fifer. The final session of Day 4 was cut short due to rain as just 11 overs were bowled in the 2nd Indian innings. You already know what happened on Day 5. India created history!

Rohit Sharma was looking in a good nick before throwing his wicket away towards the end of Day 2. Day 3 saw India get pushed further back as they lost the 6th wicket for 156. Then came the stand that has defined the Indian contingent on this tour. Washington Sundar and Mohammed Siraj put on a brave fight and went onto make their debut half ton in the process of their 123-run stand. And they reduced the lead quite spectacularly. Josh Hazlewood was the main man for Australia who got a fifer. Playing his 100th Test, Lyon had a tough day, getting just a wicket in the innings.

Earlier in the game, Australia won the toss and opted to bat on a friendly batting wicket. The Aussies posted 369 in the first innings with Labuschagne hitting a ton and skipper Paine getting to a half-century. At one point, the Aussies were in a position to post an even bigger total but that didn't happen. The inexperienced bowling unit of India did well to bounce back on Day 2. Debutant Sundar and Shardul got 3 wickets apiece.

What about Australia? Well, they threw everything they had with them to the Indians. Cummins gave it his all. Lyon, the man playing his 100th Test did everything he could do but things just didn't fall in place for them. They were made to toil hard in the field and eventually, they failed to get past the inspired Indian batters.

But Pant is Pant! He is a dasher, they say. But boy, in this innings, he showed why India should back him. If not as a keeper-batsman, then purely as a batsman. What a sensational knock. He controlled his emotions early on when Lyon tossed the ball outside off. He backed himself to go for the big shots as and when needed and turned things around superbly for India. What a champion knock from this champion player. He got lucky too but remember, luck favors the brave. To lend him support in the middle, Sundar played a nice cameo as they both stitched a 50-run stand.

Right! Let's talk about Day 5, the historic day! India needed 324 to win. Australia needed 10 wickets. The notion was that India might not want to go for the win as a draw will mean they keep the trophy. And they lost Rohit early. Gill and Pujara combined for a brilliant partnership. Gill played a gem of an innings but fell 9 short of what could've been his debut ton. He went. But what about Pujara. Well, he hung in. Got hit everywhere on the body. Looked in pain but grinded it out and took India close along with Pant. Australia looked clueless. They opted for the second new ball. Cummins removed Pujara. Australia got an opening. Well, they might have thought so.

Phew! What a game! What a turnaround! The Indian team and the big contingent is thanking the fans who came in numbers to support the Indians, away from home. Shubhman Gill with the tri-colour in his hand. The young brigade of the team. It is the same team that was crushed for 36 in the first Test and then this. Walking with pride, all around the ground. Sensational! It is a back-to-back series victory for India in Australia.

GRIT! COURAGE! CONFIDENCE! PATIENCE! FIGHT! You show all this and you win! And India have done that. They have breached the Aussie fortress at the Gabba! The Indians from the pavilion race to the middle and it is celebration time in the Indian camp. Pant is getting tightest of hugs from the Indian support staff. What a moment! What a performance. Take a bow, India!

FOUR! Here's the winning runs! Here's the history! Here's Rishabh Pant! Josh wants to bowl it wide outside off. He ends up dishing a low full toss. Pant drills it through mid off. The fielder in the ring cannot stop and the ball races away to the fence. Take a bow, Rishabh Pant! What a game! INDIA WIN BY 3 WICKETS AND TAKE THE SERIES 2-1.
Full and down the leg side. Pant looks to hammer it down the leg side but misses to connect. Was way down the leg side.
Who comes out now with 3 required? Navdeep Saini is the new man in but he won't be on strike as the batsmen crossed ends.

OUT! CAUGHT! Shardul departs now! This match and this series just keeps throwing surprises. A fuller ball on the pads, Shardul looks to flick but ends up getting a top edge. The ball ballloons towards mid-wicket. Lyon settles under it and takes the catch. Good thing for India is that Pant is still there and they have crossed as well.
They take two! Splendid running. A length ball around middle, Shardul clips it through square leg. They go for the second and make it in the end. Excellent running.

In the air... safe! WOW! Pant survives a scare! Rahane in the stand cannot believe it. A fuller ball outisde off, Pant looks to go big and finish the game. He miscuies it. The ball goes high in the air towards point. Wade cannot get under it. Pant takes one. India just a hit away. 5 is what they need.

FOUR! SHOT! Pant wants to end this quickly. A short ball around off, Pant wanted to duck first and then manages to pull it. It is wide of the man at fine leg. And it races to the fence. Pant is on the ground as he loses his balance. What a shot.
Flat and just outside off, Shardul keeps it out off his back foot. Successful over for Lyon but India need just 10 more.
Shardul Thakur comes out to bat now. Just 10 required for them to create history.

OUT! TIMBER! Lyon removes Sundar. Twist in the tail? Poor shot attempted from Sundar. He cannot believe it. A tossed up ball outside off, Sundar looks to reverse sweep but ends up dragging the ball onto his stumps. Lyon has 399 wickets now. Sundar has done his job though. He would've loved to stay till the end but that's not to be. A fine, little cameo nonetheless.
Tossed up and outside off, Pant sweeps it through mid-wicket and takes three. Just 10 needed now.
Flatter and outside off, Pant looks to cut but misses.
Short and wide outside off, Sundar slashes it to deep cover for one.
Tossed up and outside off, Pant drill the drive through point for a single.
Beaten! Lovely ball. Pitches this just outside off and makes it to come back in. Sundar looks to defend but is beaten.
Good length and around off, pushed to mid off.

FOUR LEG BYES! More runs! More runs for India. Luck going their way now. The shoulders are down now, as far as the Aussies are concered. A length ball around off and middle, Sundar looks to work it on the leg side but misses to get hit on the pad. The ball then goes over the gully region and into the fence at third man.

Smart again! Pant is keeping his cool here. Sensible from the southpaw. A length ball around off, Pant tucks it through square leg. Takes the first one hard and wants the second but decides against it in the end. Just 19 needed now.
Length ball around off, Pant tucks it towards square leg and scampers back for the second. Brilliant running between the wickets. Pant had to dive to make his crease. Direct hit would've been close.

Two now! Smart from India. A length ball around off, Pant tucks it towards the off side and goes for a single. The fielder there has a shy with an underarm throw. He misses. They take one extra as overthrow.
Here's Josh Hazlewood. Can he do some magic? Is India on the cusp of creating a history of winning back-to-back series down under?

Two more! Full and wide outside off, Sundar nails the drive wide of the man at deep cover for a brace. 15 from the over. 24 more needed for India. 6 overs left for them to do the job. Australia need 5.

FOUR BYES! What happened there? India won't care. Lyon tosses it up and outside off, it pitches and then turns in sharply. Sundar lets it be. Paine has no chance of gathering that. No chance at all. To make the matter worse, it races to the fence.
Full and wide, Pant reaches out and drives it towards deep point for a single.

FOUR! TAKE THAT! Pant is turning it on here. Consecutive boundaries. A tossed up ball around off and middle, Pant goes for the slog sweep and nails it to the deep mid-wicket fence. This is just amazing batting.
FOUR! WOW! Time for some T20 cricket. A tossed up ball around off and middle, Pant moves inside the crease and paddles it through short fine leg. Finds the boundary.
Darted outside off, left alone.
EDGY FOUR! India won't mind. A length ball outside off, Sundar looks to slam it over the off side but the ball takes the outside edge and flies to the thrid man fence. 39 more needed.

SIX! WOW! Sundar, what a shot! What a shot! A short ball around middle and leg, Sundar swivels and nails the pull over fine leg for a biggie. That is a stunning shot against world's number 1 bowler. There was a man there for the catch but boy Sundar connected it superbly.
Shortish and around off, punched towards point.
Uppish but safe! Full and outside off, Sundar drives it uppishly. It falls well short of the man at mid off.
Fuller and around off, clipped through square leg for a single. Wanted the second but they decide against it.
A sharp bumper on middle. Pant sits under it.
Shortish and just outside off, Pant cuts it to deep point for a single. India need 50. Australia need 5. 48 balls left.
Shortish and just outside off, stroked to deep point for a single.
played back to the bowler.
Tossed up and outside off, drilled down to deep cover for one.
And again! This is superb from Lyon. Tosses it up and just outside off, this one pitches and breaks away as Pant looks to defend. Top ball.
Play and a miss! Tossed up and outside off, Pant looks to slam it over long off but misses.
Sharp bouncer on middle, Sundar sways away from the line of the ball.
Short and on middle, Sundar looks to fend it away to the leg side but ends up getting a soft leading edge to the off side.
Full and around off, Sundar drives it hard but finds mid off.
Good length and around off, Sundar is solid behind the line to block.
Short and on middle, turned on the leg side.
Short and wide, Sundar slashes it towards point. It was going to the fence but Lyon at point dives full length to his right to stop the ball. Saves a boundary.
Short and wide, Pant cuts but finds backward point. Just 2 from this over.
Short and wide, Sundar cuts it to deep cover for one.
Tossed up and outside off, Pant goes for the big shot. He ends up slicing it towards deep cover. Green there probably fails to spot it and is late to react. A single.
Short and around off, punched towards the cover region.
Tries to go for the slog sweep as Lyon tosses it outside off. Misses. Paine fails to gather but Smith does well behind in the slip to stop the ball.
Looped up outside off, Pane lets it be.
Short and around off, Sundar sways away from the line of the ball.
FOUR! Excellent shot! Full and on off, Sundar drives it past mid off and fetches a boundary to his name.
Short and down leg, ducked under by Sundar.
Full and on middle, clipped to leg gully.
Full and on off, Sundar drives it a bit uppish towards mid off but it falls short of the man there.
Length and on leg, clipped to square leg by Sunder for a couple.
Tossed up and outside off, Pant looks to go for the reverse sweep this time but makes no connection.
Loopy ball around off, driven to long off for a single.
Tossed up and around off, pushed down to long off for an easy single.
Floated around off, blocked.
This time he controls his emotions and lets it go behind to Paine.
Play and a miss! Tossed up and outside off, Pant looks to go big but the ball turns away and he fails to make any connection.
Length ball around off, pushed back to the bowler. End of a successful over from Cummins.
Shortish and on the ribs, Sundar hops and tucks it on the leg side.
Washington Sundar comes out to bat now. Is there still some twist left in this match? Can Australia capitalise on this opening and prevent their record of unbeaten run at Brisbane?

OUT! TAKEN! Agarwal falls this time. Cummins gets his man. Wade with a sharp catch. The game shows another twist here. Full ball outside off, Agarwal looks to slam it over cover. He hits it uppishly but Wade there intercepts and takes a sharp catch over his head. 4th wicket in this innings for Cummins. The number 1 bowler in the world is keeping his side in the game here. India need 63 more. Australia need 5 wickets. Game on.

Shortish and angling in. Agarwal pokes at it but misses. The ball goes behind. Paine takes the catch and appeals. A loud appeal. Cummins is certain that it has taken the outside edge. Shake of the head from the umpire. Paine goes for the review. It won't help him. Yes, it won't. Hot Spot shows nothing. Nothing on RTS either. So, Agarwal survives and Australia lose their review. They are left with just one now.
Is there an edge? The umpire thinks no. The Aussies go for the review. Hot Spot shows nothing as the RTS comes on. Nothing on it too as Australia lose yet another review. Agarwal stays on.
Shortish and around off, poked towards mid on by Mayank.
Fuller and around off, Agarwal pushes it towards the cover region.
Tossed up and outside off, Pant lets it be.
Short and just outside off, Pant slashes at it but finds point.
On off, pushed to covers.
FOUR! Fine enough to get a boundary. Tossed up on middle, swept towards square leg for a boundary.
Tossed up on middle, clipped to mid-wcket for a single.
Floated on off, punched to covers.
Nathan Lyon to bowl. The umpire has signalled the last hour of this incredible game.

DRINKS! Time for the last Drinks break of the series! The game is still not done. 90 balls. 69 runs. Pant on 51. Australia need 6 wickets. The last hour will decide the fate of the game and the series. We are in for a scintilating finish.
Full and on off, pushed to covers by Agarwal.
Length and on middle, Agarwal clips it to short leg.
On off, kept out to point.
FOUR! That went like a tracer bullet! Full and on off, Agarwal drives it past the bowler and into the fence at long off for a boundary.
Full and on middle, Pant clips it to square leg for a single.
Length and on off, Pant looks to play it off the back foot but inside edges it to the pads.

HALF TON FOR PANT! This has been a superb knock from the left-hander so far. And, as far as he is there in the middle, the Indians will feel that they are nothing but winning it. He got India close in the last game in Sydney but failed to close the deal. Pant has the chance to do so here. He gets to his 4th half ton by pushing the good length ball towards mid on. A quick single and he gets there. Can he take India home? What an opportunity!
On middle, flicked to mid-wicket.
Lenggth and outside off, Agarwal looks to push it to the off side but inside edges it past short leg for a quick single.
Full and on off, Pant drives it through covers and takes a quick three runs. 250 up for India. 76 more needed for a win.
Length and outside off once again, Pant does not go after it. Hazlewood oversteps! NO BALL CALLED!
Outside off, Pant comfortably leaves it.
Full on off, driven back to the bowler.
BEATEN! Length and outside off, Agarwal offers the bat as he plays away from the body but is lucky to not have edged that to the keeper or the slip cordon.
Length and angled on middle, clipped to mid-wicket for a single.
FOUR! Dispatched! Fuller and on off, Pant drives it through covers and gets another boundary. He is so quick to get the bat down in time and strokes it cleanly.
Length and angled across, Pant makes a leave now.
Fuller and on off, Pant punches it through mid off for a couple of runs.
Length and on off, Pant drives but finds mid off.

Huge LBW appeal but turned down! They do not go for the review. A length ball around off, Agarwal looks to defend but misses to get hit on the pad. They appeal but not out says the umpire. A small conference from the Aussies but they opt against the review. Replays show there was a bat involved.
Sensible! Taps the next bell around off and takes a quick run.
FOUR! Firmly driven! Full and on off, Pant drives it through covers and manages to get a boundary.
FOUR BYES! Some shape into the batsman. Length ball on leg, shapes away further down leg as Pant misses his flick. Paine fails to collect as the ball goes to the fine leg fence.
Length and around off, Pant plays with an angled bat towards point.
Length and down leg, Pant goes for the flick but fails to get wood on the ball.
Josh Hazlewood to partner Cummins with the second new ball.

Two more! A fuller ball around off, Agarwal pokes it down the ground. Cummins gets down to his right and tries to stop but misses. Two taken before the fielder from ring can collect it. End of a successful over.
SHOT! Full and around off, Agarwal pushes it down the ground and gets a brace.
In the channel outside off, left alone.
Beaten first ball. Lovely from Cummins again. A length ball just around off, Mayank feels for it and has a poke but misses.
Mayank Agarwal comes to bat now.

OUT! LBW! Umpire's call on hitting the wickets and Pujara has to go. The second new ball has done the trick for Cummins and Australia. A superb ball from the number 1 bowler in the world. He pitches this around off and it jags back in. Pujara looks to defend but misses to get rapped on the pads. They all appeal and the finger goes up. Pujara calls for the review. Let's see what the replays have to show! Doesn't look like any bat says the third umpire. Nothing on RTS either. Time for the Ball Tracker. Umpire's call on hitting the wickets. The mighty Pujara has been removed by the Aussies. What an innings from him though.

Review taken! Pujara has been given out LBW! He though reviews it. Hot Spot shows nothing on it as the RTS also shows nothing. Now comes the Ball Tracker shows it to be Umpire's call on hitting the wickets.
Fuller length ball outside off, Pujara makes a leave.

The second new ball is available now! And they are going for it straightaway. It is Pat Cummins who will have a crack with it first up. 20 overs left in the day. 100 to win for India. Australia need 7.
On off, pushed down the track for a dot.
Floated and outside off, Pant shoulders arms to it. It was very close to the off pole.
Fuller and on off, Pant dead bats it onto the pitch.
Flaoted outside off, left alone by Pant.
Tossed up on off, played to point this time.
Tossed up on off, clipped to wide mid on for a single. 100 needed for India to win.
It is drizzling now! But they want to continue. Sun is out as well.
Length and around off, Pant blocks it off the front foot.
101 runs needed for a win! Full and on the pads, clipped towards mid-wicket for a comfortable three runs.
Length and on off, blocked off the front foot towards mid on once again.
BEATEN! Nearly gone! Short of length on off, Pujara looks to cut it upishly but is beaten on the outside edge.
Full on off, defended to mid on off the front foot.
Length and going down leg, Pujara goes for the flick but misses it altogether.
Lyon is looking absolutely tired and stunned! He expected Pant to go after him on every balls but the Southpaw has controlled his emotions nicely here.
Floated around off, Pant defends.
Wide outside off from Lyon. Pant doesn't go after it again. It bounces extra as it goes to Paine.
On middle, kept out by Pant again.
Floated on middle, played back to Lyon.
Another one darted outside off, Pant lets it go again.
Outside off, left alone.
FOUR LEG BYES! Length and down leg, Pujara looks to tickle it fine but ends up getting it off his pads to the fine leg fence for a boundary. Leg byes given.

A huge shout from Starc a desperate one though but the umpire does not entertain it. A fuller length ball angled onto the pads of Pujara, Cheteshwar goes for the flick but is rapped on the pads. Starc puts in a desperate appeal but nothing from the umpire.
Length and angled on middle, Pujara looks to tuck it to the leg side but ends up getting an inside edge onto the pads.
Length and outside off, Pant slaps it towards sweeper cover for a single.
Length and around off, Pant hops and keeps it out off the back foot.
Short of length on off, Pant goes for the cut but ends up underedging towards the keeper.
The second new ball is 4 overs away now!
Comes down the track and looks to go big bit this time it takes the inner half and goes to long on. A single taken.
Full and just around off, Pant covers his stumps and shoulders arms.
Flat and around off, played back to Lyon.
Lovely from Lyon this time. Lands this fuller and just around off, Pant looks to drive but misses. Lucky not to edge.
Bowls it just around off, Pant punches it towards the cover fielder.
Tossed up but wide outside off, Pant lets it go to Paine.
Nathan Lyon comes back on. Just one over for Marnus Labuschagne.
Short ball around middle, Pant tucks it to his right and takes a quick single to keep the strike for the next over.
Lovely bouncer this time. Pant looks to pull but misses.
Shortish and around off, pushed towards the cover region this time.
Landed around off, kept out off the back foot.
In the channel outside off, Pant lets it go to the keeper.
Length and on off, Pant defends it off the back foot.
Change of ends for Mitchell Starc. Can he get a wicket or two for his team?
Short and wide outside off, Pujara cuts it hard but finds point. 200th ball for Pujara.
Full and around middle, flicked to mid on.
Outside off, left alone.
Fuller and outside off, Pujara drives it straight to the bowler who fields it and hits the stumps at the striker's end but Pujara was going no where.

FOUR! FIFTY FOR PUJARA! What a player, what a knock! He got hit on his elbow, then on his helmet. He was pinged on his fingers as well. But this man has shown some unbelievable courage, grit and concentration. He just bats and bats and bats. And here he is, at it again. Bruised, thumped, pinned and everything else but he is battling it out. Gets to the milestone by getting on the back foot and forcing this wide ball through backward point for a boundary. Superb innings. Can he take the team over the line here along with Pant? Gets to his 27th Test fifty which is also the slowest in terms of balls.
Flatter and outside off, Pujara pulls it to mid on.
Bowling change! Paine tosses the ball to Marnus Labuschagne. Can the part timer do some magic?
Outside off, left alone by Pant.
Length and on middle, Pujara whips it to the leg side for a single.

On leg, clipped to square leg by Pant for a single.

SIX! There goes Pant! What a strike! What a shot! The last ball spun away like a cobra there but Pant backs himself to clear any boundary. Lyon tosses it up and Pant comes down the track. Gets to the pitch and powers it over the long on fence. 200 up for India. They need 127 more. Australia need 7 wickets.
Big turn! Pitches on the rough or crack and went away to the slip fielder.

The ball through breaks away and goes behind. Paine cannot collect it to take the bails off. Smith at first slip cannot stop it either and it goes to the third men fence. Pant survies.

The groundsmen are out there. Some levelling done near the bowler's landing area. They hammer it to even it out. All set now to continue.
Short ball around off, Pujara sways away from the line of the ball.
Length and around off, pushed to mid off.

Catch is the shout! Didn't carry. Flat and turning in from around off, Pujara flicks. It falls just short of the man at forward short leg.
Short and wide outside off, slapped to deep cover for one.

Sharp bouncer outside off, left alone.

Shortish and outside off, left alone.
Full and around off, Pujara drives it straight, Josh gets down to pick the ball and threatens to throw at the stumps as Pujara was charging ahead for a single.
Looped up and around off, kept out by Pant. Maiden from Lyon from the other end as well.
Flatter and around off, pushed towards the cover.
Outside off, left alone again.
Full and around off, pushed towards the cover.
Another one outside off, Pant lets it be.
Tossed up outside off, Pant lets it be.
Nathan Lyon to bowl from the other end. 17-4-42-1 for him so far.
Landed around off on a good length, Pujara is solid in defense. Maiden to start from Hazlewood.
In the channel outside off, moves away far too much after pitching. Pujara lets it be.
Shortish and around off, punched towards the cover region.
Short but outside off, Pujara lets it be.
Fuller and around off, kept out.
Nervous moments! Length and outside off, Pujara initially looks to leave it but ends up getting a glove as the ball rolls to the slips.

We are back for the final session of this Test. The match is tantalizingly poised with India needing 145 runs to end Australian dominance of 31 years at the 'Gabba. Cheteshwar Pujara and Rishabh Pant are out in the middle for India. The Aussies are out too as they look to preserve their record of 31 years of unbeatability at the 'Gabba. Can they do it? Or will India breach their fortress? Action begins for the one last time on this tour as Josh Hazlewood streams into bowl.
...  Day 5, Final session ...

Right! We have got a match in our hands. 37 overs to be bowled, weather permitting. India need 145 runs. Australia need 7 wickets. Pujara, the blocker is out in the middle. Pant, the dasher is there too. There's Cummins as well and so is Lyon. Both of them bowled decently in this session. But, do they have in them to do some magic with the ball in this final session? Or will the Indians be able to scale the total down and breach the Aussie fortress here at Gabba? We will find out all in the final session. Join us for the same in a short while.

The Aussies attacked relentlessly with the ball. They kept bowling bouncers. Gill had no issues dealing with it as he pulled and cut. In one of Starc's over, the Indians took 20 and pushed the Aussies on the back foot. However, Lyon prized out the wicket of Gill to deny him a hundred. Pujara was troubled by the Aussie quicks with nasty short bowling but they once again couldn't get his wicket. Cummins got the wicket of the Indian skipper to take some control in the game. However, once again, they were not at their best which can be confirmed seeing the runs they have given in this session.

The session started with Gill and Pujara battling it out as the Aussie quicks continued the barrage of short stuff. However, Gill and Pujara took them on and played a few superb strokes. Pujara got hit on the helmet, on the elbow, on the fingers. But the tough man continued the battle. Gill fell 9 short of a well-deserved ton. Rahane walked out with a positive mindset but couldn't carry on as he departed for 24 off just 22 balls. Pujara has continued his battle and has faced 168 balls for his 43. He has Pant for the company for the final session.

Another terrific session ends! Once again one would assume it is India who have edged out the hosts. They have scored 100 runs in 25 overs and have lost just 2 wickets. Pujara is continuing his vigil in the middle. With Pant at the other end, the third and final session of this Test match promises to be a cracking one!
Length and on off, pushed to covers. THAT WILL BE TEA ON DAY 5!
BEATEN! Length and angled around off, Pant hangs his bat out in defense but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Another length ball on off, Pant blocks it off the back foot towards short leg.
Length and on off, kept out.
Good length and around off, Pant looks to defend it out but ekes out an inside edge onto the box.
Length and on off, Pant pushes it to point.
Loopy on off, Pujara pushes it off the back foot towards short mid-wicket.
Floated on off, clipped towards short mid-wicket.
Flatter outside off, Pant slaps it through point for a single. 100 scored in this session so far.
Floated outside off, left alone.
Floated outside off, turning away, Pant leaves it.
Tossed up on off, Pant drives it through covers and gets a couple.
A short one on off, Pant pulls it as he takes his eyes off. The ball goes behind square on the leg side for a single.
Length and targetting the stumps, Pant defends it from within the crease.
Another fuller one on off, Pant plays it towards covers.
Length and on off, pushed to mid off.

FOUR! Pant gets into the act there! Though it is edgy but India will take it. Back of a length ball around off Pant pushes at it with hard hands. The ball takes the outside edge and goes through the gully region and towards third man for a boundary.
Short one down leg, Pant lets it be.
Floated and around off, Pujara defends.
Flat and around off, this time Pujara is solid in defense.

Miscommunication but safe in the end. Fuller and middle, Pujara whips it towards mid-wicket and takes off for a single. Cummins at mid-wicket gets to the ball and releases the throw to the keeper. Pujara does well to make it in time before the bails come off as he puts in a dive.
Flighted on off, Pujara plays it to short leg.
Floated on off, Pujara dead bats it on to the pitch.
Floated on off, clipped towards mid-wicket.
On off, kept out by Pant off the front foot.
Short and angled across off, Pant leave it alone.
Short and down leg, Pant looks to pull but ends up missing it.

There goes Pant! A short ball on middle, Pant take sit on and pulls it through mid-wicket. Scampers back for the second. And with that, it is 1,000 Test runs for Pant. Quickest Indian wicket-keeper to to do so.
Fuller and on off, Pant keeps it out off the front foot.
Length and on off Pant pushes it to the off side.
FOUR! Pujara helps it on its way. Flatter and on middle, pulled towards fine leg for a boundary.
Floated around off, tucked towards sqaure leg.
Fuller on middle, clipped towards short mid-wicket.
Tossed up on midlde, Pujara clips it past short leg.
Tossed up on leg, Pujara tucks it towards square leg for a couple of runs.
Flatter on off, Pujara pushes it off the back foot.
Good length and just outside off, Pant pokes it towards Green at gully who tumbles to his left to stop the ball. End of a successful over from Cummins.
Who will be the new man in? Will it be Pant at 5? Yes, it is. How will he go about the business here. Interesting.

OUT! CAUGHT! Rahane goes! Australians are elated! They have bounced back in the last few overs. In the last over he was beaten on the outside edge twice but this time he goes. A back of a length ball around off, Rahane arches back and looks to help it over to third man. He though ends up getting a glove and the ball is caught by Paine behind the wicket. 150th catch for Paine. 161 needed for India to win.
Full and on off, punched through covers and gets three runs does Pujara.
Short one on middle, Pujara ducks under it.
Fuler and on off, Pujara keeps it out.
Pat Cummins is back on.
Length and around off, Rahane tucks it to fine leg for a single.
Good stop from Lyon! A fuller one around off, Pujara hits it to the right of Lyon who dives that side to stop the ball.
On middle, Pujara manags to push it back to the bowler.
Fuller and around off, kept out.

Huge appeal! Not from all the Aussie players though. Certainly not from the bowler. Not out says the umpire. Tossed up and around offf, Pujara comes down the track and looks to work it on the leg side but he misses to get hit on the pad. The ball lobs towards short mid-wicket. The fielder takes the catch and appeals. A loud on from him, keeper and Labuschagne at short leg. Not out from the umpire. No review from the Aussies.
Tossed up on off, punched off the back foot towards covers for a single.

SIX! WOW! TAKE THAT! What a strike from Rahane! The Indian skipper doesn't want Lyon to get settled here. Lyon tosses this one up and Rahane jumps out of his crease to pump it way over the mid-wicket fence.
Short of good length around off, Pujara stands on the back foot to defend it.
Fuller and on off, pushed through to cover-point for a single.
Play and a miss! Second time he gets beaten. Length ball around off, Rahane looks to play it off the back foot but the ball bounces a bit extra to beat the outside edge of Rahane's bat once again.
BEATEN! Rahane goes for an expansive drive on this length ball outside off, gets beaten on the outside edge.
Fuller and on off, clipped towards mid-wicket for a couple by Rahane.
Length and on off, defended off the back foot.
FOUR! Pujara starting to open up now. Flatter and spinning into Pujara, Cheteshwar pulls it to deep square leg for a boundary.
Darted on middle, Pujara whips it to mid-wicket.
Fuller and on off clipped towards mid on this time.
Flatter around off, Rahane punches it towards wide mid off for a single.
Floated on middle, kept out off the back foot.
Tossed up on middle and leg, Rahane tucks it to the leg side.
Fuller and around off, Pujara blocks nicely.
Shortish and around off, Pujara is right behind the line of the ball to block.
Fullish and around off, blocked towards the cover region.
EDGY FOUR! Lucky runs! A short ball, Pujara looks to duck away but this one doesn't rise. It takes his bat and goes over the slip cordon and into the third man fence.
Fullish and outside off, it is poked towards point for a quick single.
SHOT! Fuller and wide outside off, Rahane creams the drive through the covers. Lyon chases it down and flicks the ball back in. But they run four. Excellent running.
Tossed up and outside off, Pujara pads it away.
Tossed up on off, clipped to the leg side.
Tossed up and around off, kept out off the front foot.
Flatter and around middle, clipped through mid-wicket for one.

Massive Spin! That landed on a rough and spun into Rahane who does not have any idea of how to play at it. Tossed up and outside off, The ball spins into Rahane who is on the back foot to play but the ball goes onto hit him on the pads. That was going down the leg. This should interest Lyon a bit more.
Flatter and just outside off, poked on the off side.
What's coming nexrt? Another bouncer?
No! Not a short ball. It is around off on a good length, Pujara is solid in defense.

Nitin Patel is out again. He has been out on a quite number times today. Concussion Test in progress. Pujara seems to have been fine though. A few pairs of helmet. Pujara wears one and is ready again. What a player! What a game!
Hazlewood was steaming in but Pujara moves out. Stare from Josh.

Ouch! That's on the helmet! Oh dear! That was a well-directed bouncer. Pujara looks okay though. He wanted to stay away but this one came back in sharply. Pujara was once again late in moving out of the way. And gets pinged on the helmet.
Good length and around off, Rahane pokes it between point and gully. A quick single.
Fullish and outside off, kept out.
Length ball around middle, clipped straight to the short leg fielder.
Pujara has a word with the umpire. Maybe he was telling him that he was playing the shot there.
FOUR! Nicely done! First boundary for the skipper. Short ball around middle and leg, Rahane swivels and pulls it through short fine leg for a boundary.

NOT OUT! GOING OVER THE STUMPS! Tossed up around off, Pujara comes down the track to defend but is rapped on the pads. There is an appeal and the umpire does not give in. Paine after pondering over a review and then takes it. Replays roll in and as Pujara is not playing a shot Ball Tracker comes in. It is missing the stumps. Pujara survives.

Review time! Paine just thought, thought and thought and with just 2 seconds left on the timer, calls for the review. No shots played, confirms the third umpire. Here comes the Ball Tracker. MISSING! Australia lose one of their reviews.
Tossed up on off, Pujara comes on the front foot but offers pad to it.
Tossed up on off, kept out off the front foot by Pujara.
Tossed up on off, driven back to the bowler.
Full and on off, whipped towards mid-wicket.
Full on off, whipped towards long on for a single.
Length and outside off, Pujara lets it be. A testing over from Hazlewood comes to an end.
Full and on off, driven straight to covers.
Length and down leg, Pujara lets it be.
Length and around off, Pujara blocks it off the back foot.

DRINKS! The umpires have called for the Drinks break! It looked like India will take control the way Gill was tonking the ball all over the park. However, his wicket means that the Aussies will sense an opening. Pujara has taken a few blows on the body but he is not going to flinch. He is battling it out in the middle. For now, he has skipper Rahane for the company. Not too sure about how the Indians will go now from here. We will get to know as we progress ahead in this session. Here's Hazlewood again.

Nitin Patel again! Pujara is looking in a lot of pain here. He has been hit on the body a few times but didn't show the pain even once but this time around, he is on the ground as the physio attends him. He is one tough man and he shows that here as he now gets up. Sips some water and is ready to battle again.

Ouch! That is a nasty blow! That would have pinged him hard. Short of good length and on off, this one rares from the pitch as he looks to defend. Pujara looks to fend it away but the ball hits him on the glove. He immediately threw his bat away as he grimaces in pain.
BEATEN! Length and around off, Pujara hangs his bat out but is lucky to not edge that one behind.
Who will come out to bat now? Will it be Rahane or Pant? It will be India's skipper, Ajinkya Rahane who walks out to bat now.

OUT! TAKEN! Lyon strikes! Inspired bowling change from Paine. A very sharp catch from Smith. Heartbreak for Gill as he falls in the 90s. Lyon tosses it up and bowls it outside off, nice loop and drift. Gill looks to drive away from his body. A thick outside edge flies to the left of Smith at first slip. He is alert there as he reacts quickly and gobbles it nicely. A fine, fine knock from the youngster.
Flat and around off, Gill stays back to block. Did well to keep it down in front of the short leg fielder.
Fuller and around off, kept out by Gill.
Flatter and on middle, Pujara flicks it through square leg. They run three.
Floated around off, Pujara is down the track to block.
Flatter and around off, Gill tucks it to deep mid-wicket for one.
Will Starc get another over? It is a chance worth taking for the Aussie skipper with Gill on strike. However, Paine doesn't think that way. Here's GOAT, Nathan Lyon.
Fuller and around off, Pujara plays it back to Josh.
Around off on a length, Pujara is solid in defense.
Full and around off, blocked.
Length ball on middle, clipped through mid-wicket for a single. Gill moves to 90. 200 more needed for India.
In the channel outside off, left alone.
Fuller and around off, pushed to mid on.

FOUR! Pujara's turn to smash Starc now. 20 from the over. A massive one. Another short ball from Starc and it is outside off, Pujara hammers it over backward point to find the fence. He says to Gill, if you can do it, I shall do it as well. Exceptional batting.
Down the leg side. Pujara lets it be. Wanted to flick it looked but opted against it in the end.
Good length and on the pads, flicked to fine leg for one.

FOUR! BANG! This is sensational from Gill. Three in a row! A short ball and around middle, Gill moves inside the crease and nails the pull through mid-wicket. Starc, the quickest Aussie on the turf is getting hammered here. To make the matter worse, the third umpire calls it a no ball. 100-run stand comes up between these two.
FOUR! Up and over again! Another short ball. This one is outside off, Gill waits for it and then ramps it over short third man. One bounce and into the fence.

SIX! BOOM! Gill takes on the short ball and deposits it way over deep square leg for a massive biggie. What a strike from Gill. Short and on middle, Gill swivels and nails the pull over deep square leg for half a dozen. He moves to 80. Just sensational from the young man.
Shortish and around middle, flicked towards mid-wicket.
Short ball down the leg side. Pujara is not interested. Another testing over ticked off.
Fuller and around off, watchfully defended.
Shortish and around middle, Pujara tucks it towards short fine leg.

The physio is out there. Nitin Patel is out again. Pujara getting some attention. He was hit flush on the left arm. Doing some excercise. He seems to be fine to continue. Australia trying out everything to get an opening. Can they get one quickly to spice this Test a bit?
There is a man at leg gully for Pujara. And one at short mid-wicket.
Another one on the body! A short ball around middle and leg, Pujara looks to duck under it but this one doesn't rise enough. He gets a blow on his shoulder this time.
Around off on a length, defended.
A length ball around off and middle, Gill pushes it towards mid on and takes a quick single.

We are done with Cummins' barrage of short balls. Here's Josh Hazlewood with the ball. What method will he use? Will he continue to bang it short? Doesn't look like that way for now. No one at short leg for Gill.
Superb bouncer! This is around off but Pujara does really well to drop his wrists and let it go to Paine.
Shortish and around middle, Pujara is right behind the line of the ball to block.
FOUR! Up and over! Short and wide outside off, Pujara slashes it over backward point and finds the fence. Pounced on the chance.
Shortish but outside off, left alone.
Back of a length and around off, poked towards the cover fielder.
Shortish and around off, Pujara fends it away towards short fine leg. The ball took off a touch after hitting the deck.

Another bouncer and again down the leg side. This time Paine fails to collect the ball to his left. The ball hits his gloves and goes to fine leg. They take two byes. Another barrage of short stuff from Cummins but Gill this time around has change of plans.
Another short one. This is down the leg side. And Gill is not playing at it now. Kept watching the ball all the way though.
WOW! What was that! Cummins goes full and wide, Gill lets it be. The ball lands and then takes off. Paine collects it over his head.
And again! Looks like Gill has changed his plan here. Cummins bends his back again and lands this effort ball short and on middle and leg. Gill now seems to be happy ducking under it.
Short again and Gill sits under it again.
Cummins continues banging it short. Gill sits under it.
Short ball down the leg side. Goes way over Pujara who moves away.
Back to blocking the ball as he stays in the crease to defend this short ball back to the bowler.
FOUR! Intent from Pujara. Short and wide outside off, Pujara slams the cut through the covers and finds the fence. First boundary for Pujara. 100 up for the visitors.
Landed around off, kept out.
Short again, Gill works it in front of square leg for a single.
Short ball down the leg side. Gill wanted to play at it but left it alone at the last moment.
Good length and around off, watchfully blocked by Pujara.
Fullish and around off, turned towards mid on again.
Shortish and around off, pushed to mid on.
Length and around middle, bounces a bit extra. Pujara does well to defend as he takes the hand off the handle.
Shortish and on middle, Pujara tucks it through square leg and takes two more. Good, aggressive running from Pujara.
Short ball on middle and leg, Pujara ducks.
Pujara takes a single! Yes, you read that right. Shortish and just around off, Pujara pokes it towards point and takes a run. He gets a run after 23 balls.
Takes on the short ball this time and helps it down to fine leg via a pull.
Another bumper but this time Gill sways away.

In the air but away! Short ball again from Starc and Gill once again takes it on. Goes for the pull. It is not off the middle of the bat. He though manages to clear the man at deep square leg. Lucky for Gill as he gets two more. He would've had his heart in his mouth.
FOUR! BANG! Short and outside off, Gill picks the length early and whacks it through wide mid on for a boundary.
Shortish and just around off, Gill punches it towards point.
Mitchell Starc to bowl from the other end.
A dot! Good first over from Cummins after Lunch. The last ball is shortish and around off, Pujara works it towards mid-wicket off his back foot.
Another length ball. It is around off and middle, Pujara is solid in defense.
Fullish and around middle, pushed to mid on again. Wanted a single but opted against it.
Good length and around middle, it is pushed to mid on.
Short and on middle, pulled towards fine leg by Gill for a single.
Another short one on middle, it bounces a tad extra as Paine leaps and gloves it. Gill just watched it go over him. Cummins oversteps! NO BALL CALLED!
Short and down leg from Cummins to start a fresh session, Gill does not play at it.

We are back for the second last session of this Test. It could also be the deciding session with regards to which way this Test goes. Cheteshwar Pujara and Shubhman Gill walk out to the middle to start once again India's fightback after the break. The Australian players are out too and would be raring to go and have a crack at the Indian batting. Pat Cummins to start off the session.
... Day 5, Session 2 ...

Right! India have done superbly well here! Now, another 62 overs left in the day, weather permitting. India need 245 to win the game. Will they try that with 9 wickets in hand? What about Australia? They will be disappointed. Surely. Can they strike early in the second session to open up the game? The second session of the game will most probably confirm the outcome of this game. Joins us for the same in a short while to find out.

It's been a toil for the Aussies in this session. They have got no support from the surface. And not many balls have misbehaved either. It was Cummins who struck for the hosts early with the ball as he removed Rohit Sharma. However, after that, Gill and Pujara managed to see off any threat. Cummins was superb in his 2nd spell too as he tested Pujara with a few nasty bouncers. They bowled over 36 overs in the session but the 2nd wicket just didn't come their way.

India lost Rohit Sharma early in the day but Gill looked in fine touch. The youngster played a few delightful strokes to get to his half ton. Pujara along with him battled hard. He was troubled a bit by Lyon but he kept battling. Towards the end, Cummins peppered Pujara with some nasty short stuff but Pujara once again weathered the storm and made sure he walked to the Lunch break along with Gill. The duo has added 65 with Gill scoring most of the runs.

Another terrific session's play in this Test match and the series overall. Just how it has been through the series. India will take the honours of taking the session. Australia started with an early wicket and then India with a fine riposte has made sure they once again do not allow the Aussies to take control of the game. Cummins threw a few nasty and mean stuff at Pujara and the Indian number 3 took a few blows on his body but made sure he is there with the youngster.

Huge appea for a catch down the leg side. Paine takes the catch and goes up in an appeal but nothing from the umpire. Another short ball around middle and leg, Pujara looks to fend it away as he takes the bottom hand off the handle. The ball brushes his shirt and goes towards Paine who takes the catch and appeal but nothing from the umpire. They think of reviewing it but opted against it in the end. THAT WILL BE LUNCH ON DAY 5!
After a barrage of short balls comes the fuller one around off, Pujara pushes it to mid off.
Short of good length and around off, Pujara blocks it off the back foot.
Short and on middle, Gill pulls it but not off the middle of the bat. The ball goes to fine leg for a single.
SIX! Clobbered! Gill takes the short ball on. Short and outside off, Gill slaps it over backward point and over the fence there for a biggie.
A short one for Gill, Shubhman does well to not go after it.
On off and middle, kept out. Australia looking for a wicket with just few minutes left for Lunch.
Short and around middle, Pujara looks to fend it away but takes the blow onto his ribs this time.
FOUR! BYES! That's beaten all for the fence. Short one on off, Pujara does not play at it. Paine too leaps but it goes well over him too and into the fence at third man for four byes.
Full and on off, pushed to short cover this time.
BEATEN! Length and around middle, Pujara looks to defend it but is beaten as the ball goes to hit him high on the pads.
Short one on off, Gill pulls it but is well short of the fielder there. A single taken.
Another short of good length on off, Pujara is right behind the line as he defends it down the track.
Back of a length ball around off, Pujara hops and keeps it out to the off side.
A short of good length outside off, It does not bounce as Pujara would have liked as he is beaten on the outside edge.
A short one on middle, pulled towards deep square leg for a single by Gill.
Short of good length, Gill punches it to covers this tme.
A short one down leg, Gill sits under it.
Shortish and just outside off, Pujara moves out of the way this time. A terrific over.
Shortish and around middle, blocked this time.

Appeal for caught behind but turned down. No review from the Aussies. It is the short ball that is troubling Pujara. It is just around off and middle, Pujara looks to duck but this time he is late in moving out. Pujara takes his eyes off too. He didnd't drop his gloves this time around. The ball goes past his gloves into the mitts of Paine who takes the catch and appeals. Not out says the umpire. Terrific from Cummins here.
Another good bouncer from Cummins. It is aimed right at the body. Pujara ducks. Again the ball kisses the helmet and goes to Paine.
Good length and around off, Pujara defends it towards mid on.
Landed on a length and around off, blocked.
Tossed up and around middle, turns in as Gill lets it be. Maiden over from Lyon.
Loopy ball around off, kept out.
Another one down the leg side. Gill lets it be.
Floated around off, watchfully blocked.
Flatter and around middle, turned on the leg side.
On the pads and Gill is happy to pad it away.
Banged short again from Cummins and Pujara this time does well to move out of the way. Good testing over from Cummins.
The physio is out there. Mandatory Cocussion Tests to go on. Pujara is sipping some liquid as his helmet gets checked. All ok and set to continue. Can this break in play disturb India's rhythm?

That's on the helmet. Banged short and on middle, Pujara drops his hands and looks to get out of the way. But he is late in doing so and the ball hits him on the back of the helmet. Signals Lyon that he is fine who enquires on him.
Cummins goes full and Pujara pushes it to mid on. Calls for two straightaway and Gill respinds to make it in the end.
Extra bounce! This one pitches around off on a good length, it bounces extra but Pujara does well to get on his toes and blocks.
Landed around off on a good length, kept out.
Good length and around off, Pujara pokes it towards point.
On off, blocked.
Tossed up on middle, clipped towards mid-wicket for a couple of runs. 50-run stand is also up between these two.
Flicked straight to Wade. He is looking in some pain. Flat and around off, Gill goes back and flicks it hard. The ball bounces in front of the short leg fielder and then hits him near the chest.
Full and just aroudn off, Gill goes for the sweep. Nails it but finds square leg.
Looped up and outside off, pushed to mid off.
Looped on the pads, padded away by Gill.
Very full and around off, blocked.
This one is an easy leave as it is wide outside off.
Good leave! That wasn't too far from the off pole. This one is pitched outside off. It comes back in as Pujara lets it go to the keeper. Trusted the bounce there.
Landed around off on a length, blocked.
Fuller and around off, pushed to mid on.
Ouch! Banged short and on middle, Pujara ducks but this one doesn't get up as much as Pujara thought. Gets hit on the shoulder.
Pat Cummins comes back on. 6-4-4-1 from him so far.
Darted on the pad, Gill pads it away.
Floated around off, Gill blocks off his front foot.
Shortish and just around off, punched straight to the cover fielder.
Flatter and around middle, kept out.
Another one down the leg side. Gill lets it be.
On the pads, Gill pads it away.
Banged short and on middle, Pujara sits under it.
In the channel outside off, left alone.
Good length and around off, Pujara blocks it nicely.
Shot! Full and on middle, Gill flicks it past the man at mid on who gives it a chase and stops it near the fence. Not before Gill takes three though.
Landed around off on a length, kept out.

FIFTY FOR GILL! A fine knock from the youngster so far. He saw his opening partner depart early but he has kept things flowing for the Indians. He gets the milestone by punching the short ball outside off through cover-point. A huge round of applause for the young man. His 2nd half ton in Tests. Can he convert this one into a three-figure score here?
Flatter and around off Pujara comes down the track and looks to defend but the ball takes the inner half and goes towards the leg side.
On off, poked towards point.
Lopped up outside off, Pujara looks to pad it away but the ball turns just a touch to go behind.
Tossed up on middle, clipped to mid on.
Full on off, driven to long on for a single.
FOUR! Beautiful shot! Too full around off, Gill drives it through covers for a boundary. Moves to 47 with that.
Length and just outside off, Pujara does not want to play at it.
On off, kept out by Pujara from within the crease.

Full and on middle, Gill clips it to wide mid on and takes off for a single. The fielder from mid on gets to the ball and scores a direct hit at the keeper's end but Pujara dives to make his crease. He is safe.

We are all set to begin the final day of this Test as Rohit Sharma and Shubhman Gill stride out to the middle. The Australian players are out in the middle too. Josh Hazlewood will finish off his over from overnight with one ball remaining.  98 overs to be bowled, India need 324 more for a win, Australia need 10 wickets. Here we go...

Shardul Thakur is down for the chat. Thakur says that he is good. Mentions that everything comes down to the final day. He mentions that Rahane just spoke general things as to play confidently. He also says that he enjoyed his batting. On the bowling, he says that he just tried bowling in the channel and get wickets. Further says that he got wickets in the first spell and that made it easy for him. He also says that swinging the ball is his forte and it comes to him naturally. Also says that you just don't come and win the series in Australia and says that they just look to win here or take out a draw today.

Pitch Report - Glenn McGrath says that there are quite a few cracks in the center and as seen yesterday Siraj used it to good effect. Ends by saying that the Australian bowlers would look to exploit those areas too.

What about the weather then? It is not raining currently but there was heavy overnight rain. Though the ground has dried up well as we have an on-time start. Still, the conditions are overcast and with a heavy cloud cover, the pitch could play a few tricks.

India played just 11 balls before the rain arrived to steal away any further possibility of play on Day 4. Still needing 324 runs for a win. What will be India's approach? If they win or draw they will keep the Border-Gavaskar Trophy. What about Australia's mindset? The 5th-day blunder of Sydney would be fresh in their memory as they would look for a win here and extend their dominance at the 'Gabba.

Then, Paine, Green, Cummins played cameos to take Australia to a lead of 327 runs. For India, with the ball, it was Mohammed Siraj and Shardul Thakur. The former bagged his maiden Test 5-fer as the latter ended with a 4-wicket haul. In between, Sundar was impressive with the ball in the second innings too.

Coming to this Test, Day 4 saw a rain-marred last session but before that Australia unleashed their killer instincts with Warner and Harris going bonkers. Though both fell in quick succession, Smith continued his work as Labuschagne the centurion from the first innings departed for 25 as Wade followed him soon.

It's the final day of this long Australian tour. India have done well so far on the tour. Having lost the ODIs and won the T20Is. The tour further moved on to the coveted Test series. If the first was pocketed by Australia, then second was of India. Then a historic draw at Sydney meant that the final Test of this series was fought with the series on the line.
... Day 5, Session 1 ...

Right! That's all the action from Day 4 And, in the days when we are seeing Tests getting wrapped up in 3 or 4 days, another Test in this series is going to Day 5. And to make things interesting, we still have the possibility of all three results. So, bring it on, Day 5. The action will begin at 0930 local (2330 GMT PREVIOUS DAY). Join us for all the action on Day 5 then. For now, we bid you goodbye. Take care!
The Indians came to bat for 1.5 overs. Rohit and Gill negotiated that without any trouble before rain revisited the Gabba and forced an early end to the day.

You got to credit the Indians again. They were pushed against the walls early on with Warner and Harris looking in full swing. Thakur provided the breakthrough and Sundar got better of Warner quickly. Before Labuschagne could play a big knock, his little cameo was cut short but a jaffa from Siraj who sent Wade packing in the same over. Siraj also removed well-set Smith for 55. However, it was more about Shardul in the 2nd session as he kept things tight at his end and got a couple of wickets too. Given the kind of experience this Indian bowling unit has, they deserve a lot of credit to not allow the Aussies to run away with the game. Siraj got his maiden fifer in the process while Shardul finished with a 4-fer.

It started with Warner and Harris going bang, bang! They added brisk runs and put the inexperienced Indian bowlers under pressure. However, they bounced back with quick wickets as Harris and Warner were removed in back-to-back overs. Labuschagne too fell after playing a few good strokes. Smith, continued his good form and scored a fine half ton before getting dismissed. Green and Paine too played handy knocks before the rain arrived. We eventually returned for the final session after a brief delay. The Aussie batters threw their bat at the ball and added a few more runs before getting bundled out for 294, setting India the target of 328.

And the final word has come! It is Stumps on Day 4! It looks like the rain has settled in for a long innings at the moment and seeing that the umpires have decided to call it over for the day. But a superb day of cricket nonetheless.
